GIT BRANCHES !!

It is an essential part of GIT. 
They enable us to create separate contexts where we can try new things, or even work on multiple ideas in parallel. 
If we make changes on one branch, they do not impact other branches unless we merge the changes. 

> The Master Branch - 
-- In GIT, we are always working on a branch. 
   The default branch name is Master. 
   It doesn't do anything special or have fancy powers. It's just like any other branches. 
   Many people designate the master branch as the "official branch" for their codebase, but that is left to you to decide. 

* In 2020, Github renamed the default branch from master to main. 

> HEAD -
--Head is simply a pointer which refers the current location in your repository. 
  It points to a particular branch reference. 

> Commands -
  -- Viewing branches 
     [ git branch] -> It shows and lists you the current branches.
  -- Creating and Switching Branches 
     [ git branch <branch-name> ] -> It will create a new branch. 
  -- Switching branches 
     [ git switch <branch-name> ] -> Once, we have created a new branch, we can switch with this command. 
   ** We can't see the modification of files, which we have added to the other other branches. 
      Even if we delete any contents of the file committed to one branch, it will not impact the other branches. 
  -- Another way of switching .
     [ git checkout <branch-name> ] -> Checkout command does a million additional things, that's why we use switch. 
  -- Creating and switching branches together 
     [ git switch -c <branch-name> ] -> It will create and switch at the same time. 







